  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and agreements form a framework that encourages and sometimes mandates cooperation between countries in preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering. Here are some of the most important:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of money derived from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the proceeds of all serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in asset forfeiture.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and criminalizing the laundering of the proceeds of corruption.\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a treaty, the FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. FATF's 40 Recommendations are considered the global standard and are implemented by most countries. Non-compliance can lead to sanctions and reputational damage.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention):** This convention focuses on European countries and promotes cooperation in identifying, tracing, freezing, and confiscating the proceeds of crime. It has been updated and supplemented by subsequent protocols.\n\n*   **EU Directives:** The European Union has issued several directives on anti-money laundering (AML) that its member states are required to implement into their national laws. These directives set standards for customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and other AML measures.\n\n**Key Aspects of International AML Laws:**\n\n*   **Criminalization:** Requires countries to criminalize money laundering.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Requires financial institutions to identify and verify the identities of their customers.\n*   **Record Keeping:** Requires financial institutions to maintain records of transactions.\n*   **Reporting Suspicious Transactions:** Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities (Financial Intelligence Units or FIUs).\n*   **International Cooperation:** Promotes cooperation between countries in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses, including sharing information and providing mutual legal assistance.\n*   **Asset Forfeiture:** Encourages or requires countries to confiscate the proceeds of crime.\n\nIt is important to note that the specific laws and regulations implementing these international standards vary from country to country. However, the overall goal is to create a global framework that makes it more difficult for criminals to launder money and use the proceeds of crime.\n",
